# other help items:

  triplot.ini (initialization file)
  -options (command line options)
  $-variables
  ^-functions
  control-c
  Xdefaults   
  interactive mode
  building your own commands

  Type "help <item>" for more information on a specific <item>

# alpha angle

  changes the angle parameter "gamma", "theta" and "phi" (see "gamma")
  in such a way that in subsequent plots the geometry will be rotated over
  <alpha> degrees downward around the horizontal screen axis in respect to 
  the present plot.

# beta angle

  changes the angle parameter "gamma", "theta" and "phi" (see "gamma")
  in such a way that in subsequent plots the geometry will be rotated over
  <beta> degrees to the right around the vertical screen axis in respect to 
  the present plot.

# alias [name[=definition]]

  Defines a Unix-style alias. For example, the command
  
  alias mycommand=~/bin/myinputfile
  
  makes "mycommand" equivalent to "~/bin/myinputfile".
  The command
  
  alias txt=ctext 500,500,
  
  makes "txt sometext" equivalent to "ctext 500,500,sometekst".
  commonly used alaises are best defined in triplot.ini.

# unalias name

  Undefines an alias; see "alias".

# aspect value

  Set the aspect ratio (i.e. the x-size of a pixel divided by its y-size)
  of the display. The programs by default sets it to the appropriate value, 
  but you can change it, if you know better.

# autostop toggle

  If "autostop" is false, triplot will ask for input from the console
  if there are no longer commands available from a command file.
  If "autostop" is true, triplot will terminate in this situation.

  Type "help toggle" for instructions how to set or reset a toggle.
  
# back toggle

  back determines whether the current geometry's backside is plotted
  by plot, isoplot and funplot.
  If back is true while fill is false, both back and front are plotted 
  by "plot" (back in color "backcol" or dashed for monochrome displays).
  In all other circumstances only the backside is plotted if back is true.

  Type "help toggle" for instructions how to set or reset a toggle.
  
# bar hidden | toggle

  If bar is true, a color bar will be plotted after each funplot command.
  Furthermore the right 15% of the screen is allocated for the color bar.
  Reset bar to use the complete screen.
  
  If bar is set to "hidden", plotting occurs as if bar was active
  (i.e. a portion of the screen is reserved), but the color bar is not
  plotted. This option is usefull for preventing different colorbars to
  be plotted for different funplots with different scaling.

  Type "help toggle" for instructions how to set or reset a toggle.
  
# bold number

  Determines the boldness of the lines that the program draws. Number is
  a floating point number; default is 1.0.
  
# clear

  Resets program parameters to default values.

# clip clip_min,clip_max
  clip incl | excl
  clip

  If clipping is enabled, only triangles whose vertices are all between
  clip_min and clip_max from the origin (in the observation direction)
  are plotted. Clipping is enabled by supplying the values clip_min and
  clip_max, and disabled by entering "clip" without parameters.
  
  If you specify "clip incl", triangles with some vertices within the
  clipping range are included, if you specify "clip excl", they are
  not (this is default).

  When using clipping with "light on", it is advisable to set
  "fixlight on" (see fixlight).

# boxclip x_min,x_max,y_min,y_max,z_min,z_max
  boxclip incl | excl | in | out
  boxclip

  If box clipping is enabled, only triangles whose vertices are all within
  (or without) a clipping box in the object reference frame defined by 
  the parameters are plotted. Box clipping is enabled by supplying the 
  values x_min etc, and disabled by entering "boxclip" without parameters.
  
  If you specify "boxclip incl", triangles with some vertices within 
  the clipping range are included, if you specify "boxclip excl", they 
  are not (this is default).
  
  If you specify "boxclip in", triangles within the box are plotted
  (default), if you specify "boxclip out" triangles without the box
  are plotted.

  When using clipping with "light on", it is advisable to set
  "fixlight on" (see fixlight).

# planeclip nx, ny, nz, d
  planeclip nx, ny, nz, rx, ry, rz
  planeclip incl | excl | in | out
  planeclip

  If plane clipping is enabled, only triangles whose vertices are closer to
  (or further from) the origin than the plane defined by nx.x+ny.y+nz.z=d
  (so the plane with normal (nx,ny,ny at distance d from the origin)
  are plotted. In the second form of the planeclip command displayed above, 
  the value of "d" is computed from "rx, ry, rz", which is interpreted as
  a vector within the plane.

  Plane clipping is enabled by supplying the values nx etc, and disabled by
  entering "planeclip" without parameters.
  
  If you specify "planeclip incl", triangles with some vertices within 
  the clipping range are included, if you specify "planeclip excl", they 
  are not (this is default).
  
  If you specify "planeclip in", triangles closer to the origin are plotted
  (default), if you specify "planeclip out" triangles further from the
  origin are plotted.

  When using clipping with "light on", it is advisable to set
  "fixlight on" (see fixlight).

# sphereclip x,y,z,r
  sphereclip incl | excl | in | out
  sphereclip

  If sphere clipping is enabled, only triangles whose vertices are all within
  (or without) a distance r from (x,y,z) in the object reference frame 
  are plotted. Sphere clipping is enabled by supplying the values x,y,z,r,
  and disabled by entering "sphereclip" without parameters.
  
  If you specify "sphereclip incl", triangles with some vertices within 
  the clipping range are included, if you specify "sphereclip excl", 
  they are not (this is default).
  
  If you specify "sphereclip in", triangles within the box are plotted
  (default), if you specify "sphereclip out" triangles without the box
  are plotted.

  When using clipping with "light on", it is advisable to set
  "fixlight on" (see fixlight).

# checkbreak

  During the execution of a loop, the loop is aborted if a mouse button is
  pressed when the "checkbreak" command is active.

# column number

  Sets the active column, i.e. the column of the current funfile that
  is to be used used in isoplot and funplot.

# cdis number

  Synonym of "crossdis", created on behalf of dr. Huiskamp (see "stop "),
  who has difficulty with long words.
  See "cross".

# crossdis number

  See "cross".

# diffuse number

  Set the diffusion fraction to "number".
  See "light" for full explanation.

# echo toggle

  If echo is true, commands read from a "replay file" (see 'replay' or '@')
  are echoed.

  Type "help toggle" for instructions how to set or reset a toggle.
  
# funscal funmin[,funmax] |  | s | c | sc | cs | lin | log [n]

  Sets the minimum and maximum function value for funplot.
  If you enter "funscal" only (without a number), the minimum and maximum
  values of the current funfile are taken.
  If you give funscal with one value, the scale will be between zero
  and that value.
  If you "funscal s" symmetric values (around zero) are taken,
  that enclose the minimum and maximum values of the current funfile.
  If you enter "funscal c", the minimum and maximum values of the present
  active column (see "column" command) are taken.
  Options "s" and "c" can be combined.
  If you enter "funscal lin" or "funscal log", the scaling will be
  linear or logarithmic respectively. See "logfun" for full description of
  logarithmic scaling.
  
  See "funplot" for full description.

# logfun

  logarithmic color scaling for funplot is enabled by the command
  "funscal log [n]". In this case, prior to plotting the function value f
  will be mapped to:
  
     sign(f) * log(1+s*abs(f))
  
  where s is a scaling factor defined as:
   
      s = n / max(abs(funmin),abs(funmax))

  where n is the optional parameter in the command "funscal log [n]"
  (default value 1000). The larger the value of n, the "sharper" the
  mapping. For small values of n, the scaling approaches linear mapping.
  For large values, it approaches linear mapping for large function
  values.
  Note that the mapping leaves the values 0 and +-max(abs(funmin),abs(funmax))
  invariant; only intermediate values are effected.

# fixlight toggle

  If "fixlight" is false (default), the program will use the maximum
  grey scale range in each plot when "light" is on, which may result 
  in non-matching grey shades, especially when clipping (see "clip",
  "boxclip" and "sphereclip"). 
  If "fixlight" is true, true and constant grey shading is used.

  Type "help toggle" for instructions how to set or reset a toggle.

# funcolor <name>

  If the present colormap contains colors named <name>min and <name>max
  the color parameters funcolmin and funcolmax are set to these colors.
  See "funplot" for the effect of these parameters, see "defcmap" for
  colors defined in the default color map.

# funcolmin color

  The color used for values funmin in funplot.
  See "cmap" for setting this parameter automatically, and see
  "funplot" for full description.

  Type "help color" for instructions how to set a color value.

# funcolmax color

  The color used for values funmax in funplot.
  See "cmap" for setting this parameter automatically, and see
  "funplot" for full description.

  Type "help color" for instructions how to set a color value.

# lightcolor <name>

  If the present colormap contains colors named <name>min and <name>max
  the color parameters lightcolmin and lightcolmax are set to these colors.
  See "light" for the effect of these parameters, see "defcmap" for
  colors defined in the default color map.

# lightcolmin color

  The color used as darkest color when "light" is on.
  See "cmap" for setting this parameter automatically, and see
  "light" for full description.

  Type "help color" for instructions how to set a color value.

# lightcolmax color

  The color used as lightest color when "light" is on.
  See "cmap" for setting this parameter automatically, and see
  "light" for full description.

  Type "help color" for instructions how to set a color value.

# greycolmin color

  synonym of lightcolmin.

# greycolmax color

  synonym of lightcolmax.

# gamma angle

  prior to plotting, the geometry is first rotated over "gamma" degrees around
  the z (vertical) axis, then over "theta" degrees around the y axis (the
  horizontal axis in the plane of the screen), and finally over "phi"
  degrees around the z axis.

# philight angle

  Sets the angle parameter phi of the light source to "angle" degrees.
  See "light" for full explanation.

# filled toggle

  If true, the triangles closest to the observer are plotted latest for 
  "plot" and "isoplot", and the triangles are filled with the color "fillcol",
  thus avoiding overlapping triangles.
  If false, the triangles are not filled, so underlying triangles are visible.
  See "back" for interference with the "back" toggle.

  Type "help toggle" for instructions how to set or reset a toggle.

# gif filename

  Save the current image in the file "filename" in gif format. If the
  current display is not an 8-bit display, the colormap is reduced
  (smartly) to 256 colors.
  The background color will be transparent.
  For 8-bit displays the number of pixels in horizontal direction has 
  to be a multiple of 4.

# hidden toggle

  The "hidden" parameter has been renamed to "filled". It can still be used 
  for reasons of compatibility.

# buttonkey [button] [key]

  Change, in interactive mode, the function of a mouse button to that 
  of <key> (see "interactive").
  
  The left button is represented by the number 1, and the middle button
  by the number 2.

# interactive [speed <number>]

  Command modifier for plotting commands (like in "plot i[interactive]").
  If this modifier is used, control does not return to the text window
  after plotting. Instead, some plotting parameters can be changed interactive
  by mouse and keyboard control, and the graphics screen is continuously
  adapted. If the word interactive is followed by a number, subsequent columns
  of the current funfile will be plotted by funplot and isoplot in a
  movie-like fashion. <number> is the number of times the all columns are
  plotted within a second (the "speed" of the movie). The default speed is 0.
  
  A set of commands can be made interactive by including them in an interactive
  loop; see "for".

  The mouse commands are:
  left button:        rotate around horizontal/vertical axis
  middle button:      translate in horizontal/vertical direction
  right/both buttons: return control to text screen
  
  The mouse buttons can alternatively be assigned to the key function
  listed below by using the "buttonkey" command.
  
  The keyboard commands are:
  q:          quit = return control to text screen
  r:          restore =  restore original parameters and return control
  left/right: rotate around axis perpendicular to screen
  up/down:    change crossdis
  pg up/down: scale op/down
  +/-:        move column index forward/back (keypad +/- are also accepted)
  >/<:        move column index by larger steps
  s:          toggle smooth on/off
  l:          toggle light on/off
  p:          plot
  i:          isoplot
  f:          funplot
  e:          elplot
  c:          cross
  m:          perform command "mouse v m" (see "mouse")
  0-9:        set speed to 0.1 * times 0-9
  *//:        multiply/divide speed by sqrt(2)

  In an interactive "for" loop +,-,> and < act on the column index if the
  loop is invoked as 
  
      for interactive [speed <number>]

  If the loop is invoked in the form

      for interactive var=<x> to <y> [step <z>] [speed <number>]

  the above key strokes work on the variable $var, where <x> and <y> are
  the minimum and maximum value of $var, and <z> the step size between
  subsequent values of $var (default 1). This feature is useful e.g. to
  change the clipping range in an interactive way; in this example the
  range may be set within the loop by "clip -100, $var".

# light toggle

  If true, the object will be plotted as if a light source at angle
  (thetalight, philight) were present. Lightcolmin and lightcolmax determine
  the colors used as grey values. The reflection consists of a diffuse 
  part and a glimmering part. The ratio between the two is controlled
  by the parameter "diffuse". 
  If "fixlight" is false (default), the program will use the maximum
  grey scale range in each plot, which may result in non-matching
  grey shades, especially when clipping (see "clip"). If "fixlight" is
  true, true and constant grey shading is used.

  See "back" for interference with the "back" toggle.

  Type "help toggle" for instructions how to set or reset a toggle.

# lightedge toggle

  If true, the edges of thwe triangles are plotted if light is true.
  By default lightedge is false.

  Type "help toggle" for instructions how to set or reset a toggle.

# marker index/triangle/selected/none

  If marker==index,    the index of each vertex plotted by the "plot" command.
  If marker==triangle, the index of each triangle plotted by the "plot" command.
  If marker==selected, the index of the selected triangles are plotted.
  If marker==none,     no indexes are plotted.

  The scale and color of the markers are contolled by "textscale" and 
  "textcolor".

# mode

  This parameter determines which mode (i.e. or, xor, and, replace etc)
  is used for plotting. Mode is not yet fully supported.

# mri filename

  Produces a dump of the display in mri pixel format. The resulting
  file can be used as input by the program mri.

# normal x, y, z

  Sets theta and gamma in such a way that the viewing direction is allong
  (x,y,z). Phi is set to zero.

# obsdis number

  Obsdis is the distance of the observer to the origin. When plotting,
  the perspective is taken into consideration.
  Obsdis is a floating point number. If you enter obsdis on a line
  by itself, the default value (infinity) is restored.

# origin x,y,z

  Before plotting, the geometry is shifted in such a way that the point
  (x,y,z) is in the origin.
  "origin" can be abrevated to "org".

# outfile [filename]

  This command opens a file, to which the output of some commands are written.
  The file is closed by entering "outfile" without parameter.
  
  The commands that write to the output file are:
  mouse.

# phi angle

  see "gamma".

# range min,max

  Only the triangles in the ranges from min to max are plotted. When a new
  geometry file is read, min is set to 1 and max is set to the number of
  triangles in the geometry. Omitting the parameters min and max resets
  the full range.

# rowplot number [first] [last] [mark]

  Plots row <number> of the present function (see "funfile") as a function of 
  time within the rowplot window (see "rowplotwin"). If the parameters <first>
  and <last> are present, only the columns between <first> and <last>
  will be plotted. If the command is followed by the text "mark", a vertical 
  line in will be drawn at the position corresponding to the present column 
  (see "column").
  The plot is in "color", the marker in "textcolor".
  
# rowplotwin left, top, right, bottom

  Set the window in which rows are plotted (see "rowplot"). Values are relative
  to the screen size; default is 0.1, 0.8, 0.2, 0.9. Column 1 will be at
  <left>, column $ncolumn at <right>, funmin at <bottom> and funmax at
  <top>.

# vecplot [[first] [last [mark]] [arrow]

  Plots the vector loop of the present function (see "funfile"), provided
  it contains three rows. The origin of the loop is controlled by
  "vecorig". The scale of the loop is controlled by "funscal".

  If the parameters <first> and <last> are present, only the columns between
  <first> and <last> will be plotted. If the command is followed by the
  text "mark", The position corresponding to the present column (see "column")
  will be marked by a symbol (see "symbol").  The plot is in "color", the 
  marker in "symbolcolor".
  
  "vecplot arrow" draws a arrow from "vecorig" to the position corresponding 
  to the present column.
  
# vecorig x,y,z | x,y

  Sets the origin of vector plot (see "vecplot"). 
  
  In the first form, x,y,z are plot-coordinates. The origin of the vector 
  loop will be fixed to the geometry.

  In the first form, x,y,z are text-coordinates. The origin of the vector 
  loop will be fixed to screen.
  
# scale number

  "scal" controls the plotting scale. If scal==r, a sphere of radius r will
  fill the screen as complete as possible, given the aspect ratio.
  If you enter just "scal" (without a number), the scale is set such that the
  current geometry fits closely within the display.
  Scal is a floating point number.

# center

  "center" changes the values of "scal" and "origin" such, that the current
  triangle file using the current plot parameters fills the window as much as
  possible.

# size nx, ny  [ cm | inch ]
  size landscape | portrait

  In the first form the display size is changed to nx,ny. For display file 
  of type "ps:" or "cps:" the display is plotted in landscape mode if nx>2200
  and in portrait mode in any other case. If you add units (cm or inch),
  triplot will try to set the display to nx x ny in those units.
  
  In the second form the display size is changed to nx=max(nx,ny),
  ny=min(nx,ny) for "landscape", and vise versa for "portrait".

# smartps toggle

  If smartps is true, filling of triangles with varying colors or grey values
  is done by the program interpreter. This makes the resulting postscript file
  much smaller. When using a printer with a slow interpreter, smartps is better
  turned of. 

  Type "help toggle" for instructions how to set or reset a toggle.
  
# smooth toggle

  If smooth is true, the grey shades used by plot when light is true
  and the colors used by funplot are interpolated over each triangle.
  If smooth is false, each triangle has a constant grey value / color.

  Type "help toggle" for instructions how to set or reset a toggle.
  
# step number | log | lin [base]

  Step is the function value interval between isofunction lines for the
  "isoplot" command. Step is a floating point number.
  
  "step log" switches to logarithmically scaled isofunction lines; the
  optional value "base" is the base number of the log-scaling (default 2).
  "step lin" switches back no linear scaling.

  If you just enter "step" (without a number), the step is set to
  about 1/10 of the difference between the extremes of the current funfile.

# theta angle

  See "gamma".

# thetalight angle

  Sets the angle parameter theta of the lightsource to "angle" degrees.
  See "light" for full explanation.

# time number

  Synonym to "column". The time parameter is added for historic reasons.

# textscal number

  Determines the size of the text plotted by "plot". The default value is 1.0.
  The implementation is system and screen dependent.

# textfont string

  Set the text font to type "string". Possible values are:
  
  normal/default
  bold
  unbold
  symbol
  helvetica
  
  Not all fonts are available at all display types. The effect of text scaling
  may not be the same for all fonts on vga type displays.

# textrotate number

  Rotate all subsequent text over <number> degrees.
  
  Text rotation is not available on X display types.
  On vga display types, the only possible values are 0 or 90.

# vms toggle

  If true, the programs assumes that all input files are ASCII files in the 
  terrible "VMS" file structure. This toggle was added in order to persuade
  Geertjan Huiskamp into using this program.

  Type "help toggle" for instructions how to set or reset a toggle.

# xpos n,m

  The screen is logically divided into m equal segments in the x-direction,
  and the n-th segment is used in further plotting command. Output is not
  clipped within this segment.

# ypos n,m

  The screen is logically divided into m equal segments in the y-direction,
  and the n-th segment is used in further plotting command. Output is not
  clipped within this segment.

# symbol name

  Determines what symbol is used by the command "point".
  Valid names are: 
  point, plus, cross, horline, verline, rectangle, diamond, circle,
  larrow, rarrow, uarrow, darrow.

# symbolscal number

  Determines the size of the symbols used by "point", the default value is 1.
  Note that when reading points from a file the size of the symbols can also
  be controlled by the date in the file; see "point".

# backcol color

  The color used for drawing triangles directing away from the observer.
  See "back".
  
  Type "help color" for instructions how to set a color value.

# bgd color

  The background color used by cls and init as default color for clearing the
  screen.

  Type "help color" for instructions how to set a color value.

# color number/name

  Sets the color used for plotting triangles.
  
  A color may be set by a number "n", in which case it is set to the n-th color
  in the present colormap (counting from 0), or by a name "color", in which
  case it is set to the color index for which "color" is defined in the
  colormap (see "cmap").

# isocolzero color

  The color used for zero isofunction lines.
  See isoplot for full description.

  Type "help color" for instructions how to set a color value.

# isocolmin color

  The color used for negative isofunction lines.
  See isoplot for full description.

  Type "help color" for instructions how to set a color value.

# isocolplus color

  The color used for positive isofunction lines.
  See isoplot for full description.

  Type "help color" for instructions how to set a color value.

# isorange min, max

  Set the range of isofunction lines to (min, max).

# isoextr toggle

  Determines wether the extreme values of the function are marked
  separately in "isoplot" and "isofunplot".

  Type "help toggle" for instructions how to set or reset a toggle.
  
# isomarker value

  Set the density of numbers plotted on isofunction lines.
  If zero, no numbers are plotted.
  From 1 onward, the larger the value, the fewer numbers are plotted.
  
  Wether or not a fill-colored box is drawn around the numbers, is
  controlled by "text fill" or "text nofill".

# isoscal number

  Determines the size of the text plotted by "isoplot". The default value is 
  1.0. The implementation is system and screen dependent.

# fillcol color

  The color used for filling triangles.
  See "fill" for full description.

  Type "help color" for instructions how to set a color value.

# symbolcol color

  The color of symbols plotted by the "point" command.

  Type "help color" for instructions how to set a color value.

# textcol color

  The color of text plotted by various commands.

  Type "help color" for instructions how to set a color value.

# cmap filename

  The present colormap is replaced by the colormap defined in "filename".
  The first line of this file should contain the number of colors in this map.
  The next lines should each contain one color definition, consisting of
  the values for red, green and blue. After the color definition a name
  can be added; the color can than be referred to by this name. In any case
  a color can be referred to by its number, starting from zero, in the
  colormap.
  If the names "funcolmin", "funcolmax", "lightcolmin" or "lightcolmax" are
  defined in the colormap, the color parameters funcolmin, funcolmax,
  lightcolmin and lightcolmax are set to these colors respectively.
  If you omit the filename, the default palet will be loaded.
  See "defcmap" for colors defined in the default color map.

# defcmap

  On 8 bit-per-pixel displays the default colormap contains the following
  colors:

  black  red        lightred   white   green        lightblue  grey    cyan
  blue   slideblue  lightgrey  yellow  lightyellow  darkgrey   purple  flesh

  and the following color ranges (see "funcolor" and "lightcolor"):
  
  pot    grey

  On 15, 16 and 24 bit-per-pixel displays the default colormap contains in
  addition the following color ranges:
  
  hsv    tim    red    green  blue  flesh  lightred  heart

  If the default colormap is active on an 8 bpp display the request of a color
  range that is not present in that colormap, but is present in the 15+ bpp
  colormap, results in the substition of the pot- or light- color range
  in the colormap by the requested range.

# colormap

  synonym to "cmap"

# copy filename

  Creates a copy of the display to printer or file. What actually happens
  is display dependent:
  
  tx:     a Tektronix file is created (default name triplot.plt).
  xm:     a postscript dump is created (default name triplot.ps).
  xw:/xf: a greyscale postscript dump is created (default name triplot.ps).
  win:    not yet implemented.
  vga:    the program prtscr.exe is executed, with command line '1 filename'.

  If the environment variable "TRIPLOT_COPY" is defined, the value of
  this variable is used to print the file. For example, if
  "TRIPLOT_COPY='lpr -s -h -Pprt1'", and you enter the command
  "copy myfile.ps", triplot will copy the display to "myfile.ps" and
  subsequently print it by means of the system command
  "lpr -s -h -Pprt1 myfile.ps".

  If TRIPLOT_COPY is defined and you don't supply a filename,
  a random filename will be generated, and the file will be removed
  after printing is ready (by using the option "-r" in the lpr system
  command).

  a color copy (if possible) is created by ccopy; ccopy uses the
  environment variable "TRIPLOT_CCOPY".
  
# ccopy filename

  Creates a color copy of the display to printer or file. 
  
  For details see "copy".  

# cross [i[nteractive]]

  Draws the cross section of the current geometry (rotated and shifted
  according to the parameter settings) and the plane x=crossdis, i.e.
  the plane parallel to the screen at crossdis from the origin ( (0,0,0);
  not the origin defined by the "origin"command) towards the observer.

  See "interactive" for the use of the interactive mode.

# delay msec

  Pause for <msec> milliseconds.

# sync msec

  wait until <msec> milliseconds have passed since the previous time the
  sync command was given. This is particularly useful in creating animations.
  In a loop, subsequent frames often take a different amount of time to
  construct, resulting in an animation with a speed that is not constant.
  By including "sync t" in the loop, with t the duration in ms of the slowest 
  frame in the loop, the animation is synchronized.

# pause

  Pause until a key is pressed or a mouse button is clicked.

# display displayfile

  Set the display to "displayfile". Displayfile consists of a device and
  an optional filename, like "dev:name". The device controls the type of
  output. The following devices are supported:
  
        ps: postscript file. The default filename is "triplot.ps". The default
            size is 3300x2200. The size can be changed by using the command
            "size".

        cps: color postscript file.  Defaults as for ps:.

        tk: tektronix output to file. The default filename is "laser.plt"

        tx: tektronix output to xterm tek-subwindow.

  Atari ST only: low:, med:, high: (default).
  
      Unix only: xw: (default), xm:, xf: (see 'help xw:').
      
     MsDos only: vga: (default), svga: (see 'help vga:').

   Windows only: win: (default) (see 'help win:').
  
# xw: unix display

        xw: x window. The window size is controlled by the display file
            name. E.g.: "display xw:400x400" creates a 400x400 window. The 
            default size is 600x500. The window position is optionally 
	    controlled by the display file name. E.g. 
	    "display xw:400x400+0+0" creates a window in the upper left
	    corner of the screen.

        xm: line xw, but forces monochrome display.

        xf: full screen x window. The window size is controlled by the
            display file name. "display xw:400x400" creates a 400x400 window. 
            The default size is the screen size. When plotting, the display
            window is raised. After plotting the program waits until a key 
	    or button is pressed within the window and then lowers the window.

# win: Windows display

       win: MS-Windows window display type. The window size is controlled 
            by the display file name. E.g.: "display win:400x400" creates 
	    a 400x400 window. The default size is 600x500. The window 
	    position is optionally controlled by the display file name. E.g. 
	    "display xw:400x400+0+0" creates a window in the upper left
	    corner of the screen.

      winf: full screen MS-Windows window. The window size is controlled by the
            display file name. "display win:400x400" creates a 400x400 window. 
            The default size is the screen size. When plotting, the display
            window is raised. After plotting the program waits until a key 
	    or button is pressed within the window and then lowers the window.

# vga: MsDos display

      vga: standard 2-page medium resolution (640x350; 16 colors) VGA.
           page 0 is used for text, page 1 is used for graphics.
	   
     svga: Super vga (640x480, 800x600 (default) or 1024x768; 256 colors). 
           The size of the display is controlled by the display file
           name. E.g: "display svga:1024x768" sets the video to the
           1024x768 resolution. If "NxM" does not match one of the
           standard video modes, the nearest mode above those values
           is taken.
           In this mode there is only one page. Therefore the text page is 
           confined to a one-line window at the top of the display. Messages 
           are not displayed.

# edge [i[nteractive]]

  Draws the geometry's edge, i.e. the boundary between triangles
  directed towards the observer and those averted from the observer.

  See "interactive" for the use of the interactive mode.

# elfile filename

  Reads an electrode description file. The electrode description can be
  either in "index" style or in "lambda-mu" style". Each line in the file can
  optionally be followed by "!name", in which "name" is the name of the
  electrode. The electrode positions can be plotted using the elplot command.
  
# elplot [i[nteractive]]

  Plots the electrode positions as defined by the elfile command. If 
  marker==index (see marker command), the name of the electrode (or the
  index, if the name is undefined) is added.

  See "interactive" for the use of the interactive mode.
  
# exit

  While recording, exit closes the present record file.
  Otherwise exit stops the program.

# file filename

  Reads the geometry from "filename". The file can be either ASCII or
  binary. If ASCII, the file have the following format:
  
  number_of_vertices
  for (i=1; i<=number_of_vertices, i++)
    i x_i y_i z_i
  number_of_triangles
  for (i=1; i<=number_of_triangles, i++)
    i index_1_i index_2_i index_3_i
    
  In this index_j_i is the vertex index of vertex j of triangle i.
  
# for var=x to y [step z]
    ..
    ..
    end
    
  Repeats the commands between "for" and "end" y-x+1 times. 
  var is a string, x, y and z are integers. z has a default value of 1.
  In the first run through the loop, var is set to x (see "set" command),
  in the second run to x+z, etc.
  
  A useful use of the for-loop would be:
  
  for i=1 to $ncolumn
    column $i
    isoplot
    end

  "for" without parameters defines an infinite loop that can only be stopped
  by ^C or by responding "cancel" to the user input command (see "input").

  "for interactive" allows mouse interaction during the loop;
  see "interactive".

  Entering "cancel" while defining the loop cancels it.
  
  A loop can be aborted during execution by using the "checkbreak" command;
  see "checkbreak".  
  

# input [text]

  prompts for user input; mainly useful in loops (see "for"). Any
  text after "input" is presented to to user, and can be editted.

# frame

  draws a frame in the plotting color around the present (xpos, ypos) window.

# funfile filename

  Reads function values from file "filename". The file can be either ASCII or
  binary. If ASCII, the file have the following format:
  
  number_of_rows number_of_columns
  for (i=1; i<=number_of_rows; i++)
    for (j=1; j<=number_of_rows; j++)
      value(i,j)
      
  To vertex i of the geometry row i of function values is assigned. These
  function values are used in isoplot and funplot. Trailing rows are ignored;
  missing rows are set to zero.

  If the funfile contains an ascii-tail with a set of lines of the following
  format:
  
  geometry [file[s]]
  f1-l1: name1
  f2-l2: name2
  ...
  
  and name<i> corresponds to the present triangle file, the rows f<i>
  to l<i> are taken to correspond to the vertices of the present triangle file.
  If the triangle file is changed, the funfile is retained, and if the
  new name is available in the tail, corresponding action is taken.
  
# funplot [i[nteractive]]

  Plots the function defined by column "column" of the present "funfile"
  in a color scale. Values of "funmin" (see "funscal") or less are given 
  color "funcolmin", values of "funmax" or more are given color "funcolmax", 
  and intermediate colors are given a linearly interpolated color if
  linear funscaling is active, or a logarithmic interpolated color if
  logarithmic funscaling is active (see "funscal" and "logfun").

  See "gamma", "origin", "fill", "smooth", "obsdis" and "back" 
  for the effect of these parameters.
  See "interactive" for the use of the interactive mode.

# graphic

  Shows the display window. You can return to the command window by pressing
  any key.
  This command is only useful for display devices for which the display
  window and the command window cannot be shown simultaneously.

# help item

  Gives information about "item".
  
  If the information does not fit within the text screen, the program will
  pause to prevent scrolling of unread text. This is indicated by the
  prompt "--more--". In response you can press "space" to scroll up one page,
  "Q" or "Esc" to abort, or any other key to scroll up one line.

# init [color]

  Clears the display window. If color is specified, the display is given that
  color; otherwise "bgdcol" is used.

  Type "help color" for instructions how to set a color value.

# cls [color]

  Clears the display window. If color is specified, the display is given that
  color; otherwise "bgdcol" is used.

  Type "help color" for instructions how to set a color value.

# isoplot [i[nteractive]]

  Plots isofunction lines as defined by column "column" of the present 
  "funfile". The lines are drown at "step" intervals. The intervals
  may be scaled linearly or logarithmic; see "step".
  The Isofunction lines are marked by text indicating the value of that
  line. The number of markers and the size of the text are controlled by
  "isomarker" and "isoscal" respectively.
  On a monochrome display, negative lines are short dashed, zero lines are 
  long dashed and positive lines are solid. On a color display negative, 
  zero and positive lines have colors "isocolmin", "isocolzero" and 
  "isocolplus" respectively.
  If "isocolzero" is negative, the isofunction lines are drawn in a 
  color scale. Values of "funmin" or less are given color "funcolmin",
  values of "funmax" or more are given color "funcolmax", and intermediate
  colors are given a linearly interpolated color.

  See "gamma", "origin", "fill", "obsdis", "bold" and "back" for the effect
  of these parameters.
  See "interactive" for the use of the interactive mode.

# isolabel

  Plots the labels of isofunctions plotted by isoplot. In most modes, isoplot
  plots labels only if they fit within the triangles. If the triangles are
  small, few or no labels will be shown. In other modes the labels may
  partially be covered by isofunction lises drawn at a later stage.
  The command isolabel gives the opportunity to plot the labels afterwards.

# isofunplot

  This command combines the "isoplot" and "funplot" commands. The present
  function is plotted in both a color representation and isofunction lines.
  The color of all isofunction lines is "color".

  See "gamma", "origin", "fill", "obsdis", "bar" and "back" for the effect
  of these parameters.

# line x1,y1,z1,x2,y2,z2 | x1,y1,x2,y2 | @filename [f,l]

  In the first form, a line is plotted between (x1,y1,z1) and (x2,y2,z2)
  (interpreted as plot-coordinates; see "text").

  In the second form, a line is plotted between (x1,y1) and (x2,y2)
  (interpreted as text-coordinates; see "text").

  In the third form the coordinates are read from "filename". This file
  can either be a standard ascii point file (see "point"), or a standard
  ascii or binary matrix file (see "funfile") containing three columns for
  x,y and z.
  if <f> and <l> are included, only points between index <f> and <l> are
  plotted.
    
  The color is controlled by "color".

# list

  List the current values of the most important parameters.

# movie speed

  The current display window is displayed as a "movie".
  The colors between funcolmin and funcolmax are filled in by fillcolor
  at the start of each "frame", and gradually filled in by the proper
  colors. Speed is the number of frames per second.
  If you hit one of the keys 0-9, the speed is changed to 0.1 times
  the key value.
  At speed zero the control is manual; small steps by arrow up/down
  and large steps by page up/down.

# mouse [ cross | triangle | vertex | lambda | fun | text ] [ varname ]

  Display coordinates of points clicked at on display.

  mouse cross:     coordinates in 'crossdis' plane
  mouse triangle:  index of triangle
                   "mouse tf" will also flip the triangle
                   "mouse ts" will also select the triangle
  mouse vertex:    index of closest vertex
                   if a funfile is defined, the function value (for the
		   active column) at that vertex will also be given
  mouse lambda:    index of triangle and 'lambda' an 'mu' parameters
                    (see "elfile")
  mouse fun:       local function value for active column of function file
                   "mouse fp" will plot a label (see isolabel) at the site
		   of the mouseclick. The value printed will be modulo
		   the isofunction ste size (see step)
  mouse text:      screen text coordinates (see "text")
  mouse:           coordinates of projection of mouse on surface
		    
  A click on the middle button generates a symbol.
  Abort by clicking the right button.  
  
  If an "outfile" is open, the data will also be written to that file.

  If a variable name is present in the command line, the data
  is stored in the variable instead of being displayed, and the
  command returns immediately after the mouse click.

# plot [i[nteractive]]

  Plots the geometry.
  
  See "gamma", "origin", "fill", "obsdis", "bold", "light", "smooth"
  and "back" for the effect of these parameters.
  See "interactive" for the use of the interactive mode.

# 3dplot [i[nteractive]]

  Like plot, but plots simultaneously a "left-eye" version in shades
  of red and a "right-eye" version in green in order to create a 3d
  effect when viewed with red/green glasses.
  
  Use the command "colorblind yes" to adjust for the reduced sensitivity
  to red when you are color blind (an affliction suffered by the author
  of triplot and many of its most prominent users).

# raster 0 | 1 | 2

  When raster is set to 1, only half of the pixels (defined by a check board
  pattern) are actually drawn. When it is set to 2, the other half of the
  pixels are drawn. When set to 0, all pixels are drawn.
  
  This can be used to create some special effects. For instance:
  
  raster 0
  file geo1
  plot
  raster 1
  file geo2
  plot
  
  will create the illusion of geo2 being seen through the transparant surface
  of geo1.
  Triplot uses raster internally in commands like 3dplot, and funplot
  when light is on.

# point x,y,z / @filename [lines]

  In the first form, a symbol is plotted at (x,y,z).  The symbol type, size 
  and color are controlled by "symbol", "symbolsc"  and "symbolcol" 
  respectively.
  In the second form the coordinates are read from "filename". This file
  should be ASCII and have the following format:

  number_of_points
  for (i=1; i<=number_of_points, i++)
    i x y z [o_1, o_2, 0_3]
    
  If there are three optional values o_1 .. o_3 are present, they are 
  interpreted as three "strength" components f_x, f_y and f_z, and the size 
  of the symbol will be equal to "symbolscal" * norm(f).

  If there are two optional values o_1 and o_2 are present, they are 
  interpreted as a direction (similar to theta and phi) in degrees,
  and a line from the center of the symbol into that direction will be
  drawn

  If the point command is followed by the word "lines", the points are 
  connected by lines.
  If marker is set to "point" (see marker command), the index of the point in
  the file is plotted instead of a symbol.

  See "gamma", "origin", "bold" and "obsdis" for the effect of these
  parameters.

# quit

  Quits the program.

# record filename

  The file "filename" is opened, and all commands entered are written to this
  file for later use in "replay". You can stop recording by entering "stop" or
  "exit". 
  Recordings can be nested; if the command "record filename " is given while
  recording, "replay filename" is written to the old record file, and new
  commands will be written to the new record file. After "stop" or "exit",
  the commands are again written to the old record file.

# replay filename

  Commands are read from "filename", rather than from the keyboard. On end of
  file control is returned to the keyboard. Replays can be nested.
  See also "building your own commands".

  See also "record".

# chain filename

  If the program is reading input from a file instead of from the keyboard,
  chain redirects the input to another file, and closes the previous one.
  The difference with nesting of the replay command is that the input will not
  return to the previous file on end of file of the new one.

  See also "record" and "replay".

# clear

  Resets program parameters to default values.

# reset

  Resets program parameters to default values.

# rgb <color>, r, g, b, [<string>]

  Change the rgb-value of <color> (indicated by name or number; see color
  command) to (r,g,b). If <string> is provided, this will be the new name of
  the color; else it will be unnamed.

# shell

  Spawn to the system command shell (not implemented on all systems).

# stop

  While recording, stop closes the present record file.
  Otherwise stop stops the program.

# swap

  Shows the display window. You can return to the command window by pressing
  any key.
  This command is only useful for display devices for which the display
  window and the command window cannot be shown simultaneously.

# ctext [x,y,string]

  "ctext" is similar to "text", the only difference being that the text
  is centered horizontally. See "text" for full documentation.

# text [x,y[,z],string] | [ screen | world | fill | nofill ]

  The string "string" is plotted at position x,y[,z], centered vertically 
  in respect to y. 
  If the current mode is "screen", x and y run from 0 to 1000, independent of 
  the actual screen size. The upper left corner has coordinates (0,0), the 
  lower right (1000,1000). This is default.
  If the current mode is "world", (x,y,z) is interpretted as a 3D point
  in space. The location of that point on the screen is determined
  by scale, origin etc. in the same way as other 3D objects.
  
  variable expansion is particularly usefull in text; see "help $" and
  "help ^" for more detail.

  If you enter "text" without parameters, you enter text-mode, designated by
  the prompt "plot|text>". In text mode, you can enter text commands
  without preceeding "text" command.  You can leave text mode by entering 
  an empty line.

  The background of the text can be filled with "fillcolor", by
  enabling the "fill" mode. 

# loadsel name

  Loads a set of selected triangles, selected by "mouse ts" in an earlier
  session, from the file "name".

# addsel name

  Adds a set of selected triangles, selected by "mouse ts" in an earlier
  session, from the file "name", to the current selection.

# savesel name

  Save the selected triangles (selected by "mouse ts") to the file "name".

# set [name[=value]]

  "set" by itself generates a list of all user variables presently defined
  (see "help $-variables").
  
  "set name" displays the value of variable <name>.
  
  "set name=value" assignes <value> to the variable <name>. <value> may be
  any string, containing spaces, commas etc. The end of the line is the
  end of the string.

# unset name

  Deletes the variable <name>; see "set".

# update

  Force update of display. While executing loops, the display is only
  updated at the end of the loop (in order to optimize speed). Use this
  command at the point where you want to have the screen updated during
  a loop.

# parse <command line>

  If you enter a command, the command line interpreter will search the command
  line for occurences of '$' and '^'. The word following these characters is
  interpreted as a variable or a function name respectively, and the word
  is replaced by the appropriate value (see $-variables and ^-functions).
  
  Examples:
  text 100,100,$file    will print the name of the current file at (100,100)
  point ^vertex(10)     will put a marker at vertex 10
  
  "parse <command line>" will expand the command line, and print the
  result on the text screen. The command will not be executed.
  
# print <command line>

  The "print" command is synonymous to "parse".

# $-variables

  If you enter a command that contains the  string "$name", the command line 
  interpreter will substitute $name by the value of a variable called "name".

  There are two types of variables:
  
  - user variables; they are set by using the "set" command (see "help set").

  - system variables; they are set automatically by the program, and cannot
    be changed by the "set" command. The system variables are:
  
    file       the name of the present triangle file
    funfile    the name of the present function file
    step       the step size in isoplot
    column     the column of function file displayed by funplot/isoplot
    ncolumn    the number of columns in the present function file
    funmin     the minimum value set by funscal
    funmax     the maximum value set by funscal
    phi        the current value of "phi"
    theta      the current value of "theta"
    gamma      the current value of "gamma"

  See also ^-functions and the parse command.

# ^-functions

  If you enter a command that contains the string "^name(param)", the command 
  line interpreter will substitute ^name(param) by the value returned by a
  call to the function "name" with parameters "param".

  The functions that can be used are:
  
    center(indx)            coordinates of the center of mass of triangle indx
    triangle(indx1, indx2)  vertex indx2 of triangle indx1
    vertex(indx)            coordinates of vertex indx
    el(indx)                coordinates of electrode indx
    norm(x, y, z)           sqrt(x*x+y*y+z*z)
    fun(r, c)               function value at row (vertex) r and column c
    x(x, y, z)              x
    y(x, y, z)              y
    z(x, y, z)              z
    add(i1, i2)             i1 + i2
    sub(i1, i2)             i1 - i2
    mul(i1, i2)             i1 * i2
    div(i1, i2)             i1 / i2

    In the latter 4 functions 2 additional parameters may be supplied; e.g.
    add(i1, i2, min, max)   min + {(i1+i2-min) mod (max-min)}
                            i.e. the result is allways between min and max.

  ^-functions can be nested ( e.g. ^vertex(^triangle(10,2)) ).
  If you want to use the ^ character (e.g. in text), use ^^. This is replaced
  by a single ^, and the command line interpreter will not look for a function
  call to replace the substring with.

  See also $-variables and the parse command.

# binwrite filename

  Write the present file in binary format. The command "file" reads binary
  as well as ASCII files.

# toggle

  Many program parameters are toggles, i.e. they have either the value true 
  or false. The toggle "parameter" is set by any of the commands:
  
  parameter y[es]
  parameter t[rue]
  parameter s[et]
  parameter on
  parameter 1
  
  It is reset by any of the commands:

  parameter n[o]
  parameter f[alse]
  parameter r[eset]
  parameter off
  parameter 0

# @filename

  Commands are read from "filename", rather than from the keyboard. On end of
  file control is returned to the keyboard. Replays can be nested.
  See also "building your own commands".

  On Unix systems ~ is expanded to the home directory of the current user, 
  and ~<somebody> is expanded to the home directory of <somebody>.

  See also "record".

# !command

  execute the system command "command".

# #

  lines starting with # or % are considered comment.

# %

  lines starting with % are # considered comment.

# path <path>

  If command files (see "building your own commands") are not present in
  the current directory, they are searched in the directories listed in
  a search path. By default the search path is empty. This command sets
  it to <path>. The directories in <path> should be separated by colons (':')
  for unix and by semicolons (';') for dos/windows.
  
  On Unix systems ~ is expanded to the home directory of the current user, 
  and ~<somebody> is expanded to the home directory of <somebody>.
  
  Common use is to create a directory containing common command files
  (say '~/trp'), and to create a triplot.ini file (see "triplot.ini")
  in a directory within the environment PATH, that contains the command
  'path ~/trp'.
  
# triplot.ini

  If the file triplot.ini is found within the path, the commands in this
  file are executed. Command line option (see "-option"), prior to the
  first "@file" on the command line, are executed first, then the commands 
  in triplot.ini, and finally the rest of the command options (starting
  the "@file").

# -options

  A number of parameters can be set by using the command line option
  "-parameter value". The parameters you can see this way are: 
  cmap, display, elfile, funfile, and @.
  Some toggles (see "toggle") can be set in the reverse of their defaults
  values by using the command line option "-toggle". This is valid for
  the toggles autostop and vms.
  Variable x can be set to the value y by the command line option
  "-s x=y" (see "set" command).
  
  An option without - is interpreted as a file containing triplot commands
  (see "@") if the filename has extension .trp, or if <filename>.trp exists.
  Otherwise it is interpreted as the name of a geometry to be read.
  
# options

  A number of parameters can be set by using the command line option
  "-parameter value".
  The parameters you can see this way are: autostop, cmap, display, funfile,
  hidden, vms and @.
  Also, you can set variable x to the value y by the command line option
  "-s x=y" (see "set" command).
  
  An option without - is interpreted as a file containing triplot commands
  (see "@") if the filename has extension .trp, or if <filename>.trp exists.
  Otherwise it is interpreted as the name of a geometry to be read.
  
# control-c

  In Unix systems commands may be aborted by pressing control-C. If a loop
  is active (see "help for"), it is aborted. If commands are read from a file
  (see "help replay" or "help @"), reading from file is aborted and control
  is returned to standard input.

# Xdefaults

  For X systems the default values of the following program parameters are 
  taken from the server's .Xdefaults:
  plot.hlp	directory and name of the helpfile
  plot.disf	display	(display device and file)
  plot.hidden	hidden  (t/f)
  plot.vms	vms     (t/f)
  
# building your own commands

  command [p1 p2 p3 ...]

  If a command is entered that is not an internal command of triplot, the
  program will look for the file <command>.trp in the current directory, and
  read subsequent commands from that file. If the file is not found in the
  current directory, the path defined by the command "path" will be searched.

  On Unix systems ~ is expanded to the home directory of the current user, 
  and ~<somebody> is expanded to the home directory of <somebody>.

  If the command line contains additional parameters p1, p2, ..., the system 
  variables $1, $2, ... will be set to those parameters for use in 
  <command>.trp. $1, $2, ... will be set to empty lines for "missing" 
  parameters. 
  $* is set to the concatination of $1, $2, ... 
  $0 is set to the name of the command file that is executed.

